Mop-up operations are continuing in the Eastern Cape following floods. Eastern Cape officials, including Premier Oscar Mabuyane, are assessing the damage. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Eastern Cape government is engaging with national about assistance after deadly floods. Mop-up operations are continuing in the Eastern Cape. Nearly 300 people have been displaced after shacks were swept away. READ: Eastern Cape Floods | Mop-up operations underway A K9 unit police officer died while trying to rescue four farmworkers at the Nahoon River in Buffalo City over the weekend. Eastern Cape officials, including Premier Oscar Mabuyane, are assessing the damage. WATCH: Eastern Cape Floods | Gift of the Givers lends a helping hand "It’s a very painful situation, we thank the police, one person is still missing. We are getting other teams joining the search from Nelson Mandela Bay," Mabunyane said. "We are still continuing with other searches in other areas, BCM and Mdantsane and East London are affected." Humanitarian organisation Gift of the Givers is assisting with clothes and food. At least 10 people were killed in Eastern Cape floods while hundreds more are left homeless. Humanitarian organisation Gift of the Givers is assisting with clothes and food. Courtesy #DStv403